de David et de Bersabee is the focal point of Chapter 3; once again one sees the corrosive powers of love, and the ability of poetry and music to transform suffering into beauty. Mention is made of the various academies, which were important in Belleau's development. Chapter 4 traces the motif of illness in La Reconnue and links it to religious turmoil. This connection is even clearer in the Dictamen metrificum de bello huguenotico, a strange, savagely humorous text (Chapter 5). Chapter 6 concerns Belleau's poems on precious stones, surely the pinnacle of his achievement. In those, therapy is an explicitly articulated motif, while religious faith is crucial. The conclusion suggests parallels with writers such as Saint Augustine, Rabelais, Du Bellay and Montaigne.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn French.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aAcademies.  aPléiade.  aPoetry.  aecphrasis.  afaith.  agems.  ahealing.  ahumour.  alove.  amusic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT 2013z9783110317251oZDB-23-DLW0 cprintz978837656019940uhttps://doi.org/10.2478/9788376560205zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9788376560205zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9788376560205.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2013  aZDB-23-DLWb2013  aZDB-23-GOA